{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648931"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:00:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18338"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74298"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11056"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59789"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7466"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25650"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74298"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the talus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acts as a shock absorber during walking","Transmits body weight from the tibia to the foot","Supports the arch of the foot","Facilitates toe flexion and extension","Provides attachment for the Achilles tendon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe talus is one of the tarsal bones located in the foot. It is an important component of the ankle joint and plays a significant role in foot mechanics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the talus is to \u003Cstrong\u003Etransmit body weight from the tibia to the foot\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a key bone in the ankle joint, articulating with the tibia and fibula above, and the calcaneus and navicular bones below. This allows it to play a crucial role in the stability and movement of the ankle joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupports the arch of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - This function is primarily associated with the plantar fascia and other tarsal bones like the navicular\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates toe flexion and extension\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the role of the phalanges and associated tendons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvides attachment for the Achilles tendon\u003C/strong\u003E - The Achilles tendon attaches to the calcaneus, not the talus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActs as a shock absorber during walking\u003C/strong\u003E - While the talus is involved in weight transmission, shock absorption is mainly the role of the calcaneus and other structures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The talus is a key bone in the ankle joint that transmits body weight from the tibia to the foot.","The talus articulates with the tibia, fibula, calcaneus, and navicular bones.","The talus plays a crucial role in the stability and movement of the ankle joint."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59789"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59789"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T04:22:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T04:22:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11056"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74298"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela